<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="http://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 2 日星期三 18:50:20 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Movie-Theater Behavior Has Gone Off the Reels]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>剧院曾经是一个没有电话的区域。现在人们毫无悔意地使用设备。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101156"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="615" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827399?width=860&amp;height=615" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一些影迷（虽然不是图中所示）拿出手机打扰电影观众。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Iris Schneider/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101156"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-629922/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara" itemprop="url" rel="author">安-玛丽·阿尔坎塔拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 11:57（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/movie-theater-behavior-has-gone-off-the-reels-8d3ba0b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/barbie-oppenheimer-barbenheimer-premiere-e8007fe3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《巴本海默》</a>可能对剧院有利，但它却给观众带来了一些不良行为。</p><p>许多与会者忘记了一条基本规则：看电影时切勿拿出手机。相反，人们会挑选自拍照来发布，在无聊的时刻滚动，甚至打开闪光灯拍摄屏幕照片。 TikTok 正在激励新一代观众表演，甚至在社交媒体上发布他们的滑稽动作。</p><p>坐在他们旁边的影迷们必须决定是保持安静还是闹得更大。</p><p>维卡什·帕特尔 (Vikash Patel) 每周都会去佐治亚州萨凡纳看电影。这位 27 岁的便利店老板<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/barbenheimer-poised-to-deliver-blowout-weekend-at-the-box-office-9feef168?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在首周末</a>观看了《芭比娃娃》和《奥本海默》。在他的“芭比娃娃”晚间演出期间，有人在肯独白期间拍摄了照片和视频。帕特尔没有抱怨，但他说他听到他这一排的几个人在呻吟。</p><p> “电影被音乐会化了，”帕特尔说。 “你想体验电影并同时分享体验。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827621?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">身穿巴本海默衬衫的维卡什·帕特尔注意到有人在观看“芭比娃娃”电影期间用智能手机拍摄照片和视频。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：维卡什·帕特尔</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>疫情过后，公共活动的礼仪变得更加难以控制和管理。在音乐会上， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/concertgoers-are-behaving-badly-blame-tiktok-11ce4737?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">歌迷比以往任何时候都更吵闹</a>，他们对艺术家尖叫，用标语挡住人们的视线，甚至向艺术家扔东西。在百老汇演出中， <a href="https://twitter.com/ohalexsimmons/status/1646145215185448964" target="_blank" class="icon none">节目单插页</a>现在提醒人们关掉手机，让演员唱歌。现在，一些电影场馆正在发布视频来<a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@movielandcinemas/video/7121346935780330798?_r=1&amp;_t=8eLFcAYVwt9" target="_blank" class="icon none">教人们如何做人</a>。</p><p> 《芭比娃娃》和《奥本海默》 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/movie-industry-really-needs-barbenheimer-to-stretch-its-legs-18cc1ba8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">继续在票房上表现出色</a>，全球票房总收入超过 10 亿美元。这对影院经营者来说是一把双刃剑：热门电影会让人们重新坐回座位上。但如果少数与会者破坏了共享体验，更多的电影爱好者可能会等待流媒体版本来到他们的客厅。</p><h3>放映时的屏幕</h3><p>如果您想观看最热门电影的片段，只需前往 TikTok。</p><p>费城 29 岁的图书出版营销人员塞拉·穆恩 (Sierra Moon) 在首映周末拉出了巴本海默 (Barbenheimer)，甚至第二次看到了《芭比娃娃》。在放映间隙，她在 TikTok 上看到了这两部电影的场景。在她的《芭比娃娃》放映期间，她看到人们拍照并继续使用手机。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827625?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sierra Moon 看到人们在两次不同的“芭比娃娃”放映期间使用手机。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：蕾妮·米勒</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“这是我第一次注意到很多人在看电影时对屏幕拍照，”穆恩说。她认为，随着蒂莫西·柴勒梅德 (Timothée Chalamet) 领衔的《旺卡》(Wonka) 等即将上映的电影的推出，情况只会变得更糟，该片的预告片已经让 TikTok 用户陷入了一阵小小的狂热。</p><p> “现在我们在电影院的行为方式以及规则都发生了很大的变化，”穆恩说。</p><p>莱克西·韦格尔 (Lexi Weigl) 是一家营销机构的 25 岁运营协调员，她观看《芭比娃娃》时没有出现任何问题，直到电影大约看了一半。往下几排，有人掏出手机。住在佐治亚州萨凡纳附近的韦格尔说，这位女士滚动浏览了她的通知，然后翻阅相机胶卷，决定在 Instagram 上发布哪张芭比娃娃装的自拍照。</p><p>尽管魏格尔感到沮丧和愤怒，但她试图忽略它。</p><p> “我试图把注意力放在电影上，因为我正在看《芭比娃娃》，而且我是花钱来这里的，”她说。 “但与此同时，我又觉得，‘得了吧，这太不尊重了。’”</p><h3>表现出礼貌</h3><p>Alamo Drafthouse 是一家连锁剧院，顾客可以在座位上点酒和食物，过去一年来，该剧院一直<a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@alamodrafthouse/video/7145853015562390830" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 TikTok 上谴责这种行为</a>。上周，该公司在推特上发布了一张有人在观看《奥本海默》时打开闪光灯拍摄的照片，并要求客人<a href="https://twitter.com/alamodrafthouse/status/1684669409267224576" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">“在观看电影时甚至不要碰手机</a>”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><amp-twitter width="486" height="657" layout="responsive" data-tweetid="1684669409267224576" data-cards="hidden"></amp-twitter></div><p>阿拉莫公司总裁兼即将上任的首席执行官迈克尔·库斯特曼 (Michael Kustermann) 表示，阿拉莫公司训练其员工对任何在电影中扰乱秩序的客人发出一次性口头警告。</p><p> “我们了解人们的热情程度，”库斯特曼说。 “早点到那里，趁灯还亮着的时候给人群拍一张照片。”</p><p>全国各地的连锁剧院都在大厅提供社交媒体拍照机会，包括巨型芭比娃娃盒和其他布景。</p><p> “分享这段旅程的热情和兴奋的时间是在旅程结束之后，”行业组织全国剧院业主协会首席执行官迈克尔·奥利里 (Michael O&#39;Leary) 说。 “我们始终希望将电影院打造成一个特殊的地方，在那里你可以排除日常生活的干扰，花几个小时欣赏一个引人入胜的故事。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您最近在电影中目睹过任何不良行为吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><h3>电影礼仪</h3><p>在大流行期间，人们习惯了坐在家里，迅速发布他们在屏幕上观看的任何内容的照片。</p><p> “我觉得《芭比娃娃》已经成熟了——成为一部让影迷感到舒服或被鼓励去做类似事情的电影，”36 岁的克里斯·兰伯特 (Chris Lambert) 说道，他经营着一家电影解说网站，住在奥斯汀。 ，德克萨斯州地区。他在首映周末看了两遍《芭比娃娃》，还看到有人拿出手机给电影明星玛格特·罗比拍照，不止一次，而是两次。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827944?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一些剧院在大厅提供社交媒体拍照机会，包括巨型芭比娃娃盒。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：珍娜·舍内菲尔德/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>但当观众中的其他人试图摆脱智能手机并享受表演时，这种行为就不受欢迎。</p><p> “我们正处于这样一个阶段，人们很容易优先考虑在线分享某些内容，而牺牲周围人的利益，”他说。</p><p>至少现在网上有足够的“芭比”和“奥本海默”镜头，没有人需要再拍摄了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F73F494F-CBD6-4993-950C-84DD6C248F61&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmovie-theater-behavior-has-gone-off-the-reels-8d3ba0b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">影迷们涌入影院观看《芭比娃娃》和《奥本海默》的上映，有些人连续观看了这两部电影。好莱坞希望这对夏季大片的奇怪情侣能够提振票房。照片：Siemond Chan/华尔街日报<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p><em>—欲了解更多《华尔街日报》科技分析、评论、建议和头条新闻，</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>请订阅我们的每周通讯</em></a><em>。</em></p><p>写信给 Ann-Marie Alcántara，邮箱为<a href="mailto:ann-marie.alcantara@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ann-marie.alcantara@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/824b30d1-428f-4e1d-8a3e-62546516565e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 15:57:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/movie-theater-behavior-has-gone-off-the-reels-8d3ba0b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/movie-theater-behavior-has-gone-off-the-reels-8d3ba0b<author><![CDATA[Ann-Marie Alcántara]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AMD Keeps the AI Dream Alive Enough]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在今年年底推出主要人工智能芯片之前，华尔街对芯片制造商保持乐观<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104307"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="538" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828111?width=860&amp;height=538" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> AMD 在上海会议上的专区。该公司正在开发专为人工智能用途而设计的新型 GPU。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104307"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-gallagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹·加拉格尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 11:33 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMD" class="company-name">Advanced Micro Devices</a>计划以轰动一时的方式结束这一年。投资者迫不及待地庆祝。</p><p>这家芯片制造商通常被称为AMD，是今年仅次于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达的</a>第二热门半导体股票<span class="company-name-type">。</span>这意味着周二晚间发布<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-08-02-2023/card/amd-falls-after-earnings-sparks-selloff-in-nvidia-and-other-chip-stocks-rlZ68nHQKXSRoFlJ7nNi?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">第二季度业绩</a>之前，该公司股价上涨了 82%，考虑到该公司近期面临的个人电脑市场依然低迷的压力以及传统数据支出的减少，股价上涨了 82%。随着科技巨头<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-alone-cant-save-the-chip-industry-from-a-downturn-81f11199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将注意力转向实现生成人工智能所需的工具，这些</a>组件成为核心组件。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828304?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> AMD 的结果确实反映了这一现实。收入同比下滑 18%，至约 54 亿美元，而调整后营业收入则大幅下滑 47%，至约 10.5 亿美元。两者均略高于华尔街的预测，但数据中心部门的收入仍出现自 AMD 2021 年开始公布业绩以来的首次下降，并且低于分析师的预测。一个值得注意的亮点是该公司个人电脑芯片制造部门的收入，尽管比一年前下降了一半以上，但仍比目标高出 23%。</p><p>但 AMD 有一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amds-superchips-face-a-trillion-dollar-hurdle-904fa5ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">伟大的人工智能故事要讲</a>。这家成功打破英特尔在数据中心中央处理器芯片市场垄断的芯片制造商正在开发一种新型图形处理器（GPU），专为数据中心的人工智能应用而设计。这将使 AMD 与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-can-handle-being-in-the-trillion-dollar-club-1ec9e453?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能芯片巨头</a>英伟达展开竞争，英伟达的股价今年表现优于 AMD。</p><p>凭借多年开发芯片和开发人员使用的必要软件库，英伟达在人工智能领域建立了非常强大的进入壁垒。但 AMD 显然对自己的产品充满信心，因此设定了一些相当大胆的目标。该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/federal-reserve-meeting-interest-rate-hike-expected-may-2023/card/amd-bets-on-a-big-second-half-hDCm8bLurBZwtaVM9Uhc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">三个月前表示</a>，预计今年下半年数据中心收入将比上半年增长50%。在周二的财报电话会议上，该公司确认了这一目标，但补充说，大部分收益将在第四季度推出，届时该公司将推出新的 GPU 芯片。分析师目前预计 AMD 第四季度数据中心收入为 22.6 亿美元，比 AMD 2021 年开始公布这些业绩以来该领域的收入高出 37%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=419229E6-2C0B-46A8-8C1C-60F5B5BFD5BE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">自 20 世纪 80 年代以来，英特尔一直统治着中央处理器市场。但竞争对手AMD去年的市值超过了英特尔，部分原因是在芯片设计上的昂贵押注。 《华尔街日报》的阿萨·菲奇 (Asa Fitch) 解释了各公司为争夺计算机大脑而展开的斗争。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>华尔街仍然大部分支持； FactSet 的数据显示，近三分之二的分析师将 AMD 视为买入。但这比今年年初的 77% 有所下降，因为一些人出于对高风险产品发布前估值的担忧而下调了该股的评级。一些人正确地指出，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">微软</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span>谷歌和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>等正在积极构建 genAI 能力的科技巨头很高兴能有一家替代 Nvidia 的供应商。 AMD 首席执行官苏姿丰 (Lisa Su) 在周二的电话会议中指出，新的数据中心芯片将“增加我们公司的毛利率”，提振了市场情绪。花旗集团分析师 Christopher Danely 将此作为他周三将 AMD 股票评级上调至买入评级的一个因素。</p><p>尽管如此，人们对该公司盈利报告的反应不一，这表明 AMD 在今年剩余时间里可能会出现多么不稳定的情况。财报公布后，该股周二盘后交易中上涨逾 3%，但周三上午又下跌逾 6%，原因是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fitch-downgrades-u-s-credit-rating-56c73b89?mod=hp_lead_pos1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国政府债务评级大幅下调</a>，大盘面临抛售压力。与 Netflix、Spotify 和 Uber 等主要科技公司在本财报季业绩好坏参半后近期出现的下跌相比，这仍然是一个温和的反应。在这个市场上，成为人工智能军火商仍然具有一定的防弹品质。</p><p>写信给 Dan Gallagher： <a href="mailto:dan.gallagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dan.gallagher@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 15:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amd-keeps-the-ai-dream-alive-enough-36f95a84<author><![CDATA[Dan Gallagher]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>图形处理单元</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>列</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Advanced Micro Devices公司</category><category>AMD</category><category>英伟达</category><category>NVDA</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>列</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>图形处理单元</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Home Depot’s Chief Information Officer on the Role of Tech Postpandemic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这家家居装修零售商的目标是在消费者 DIY 项目减少的情况下增加并更好地服务其专业客户<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102516"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827878?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fahim Siddiqui，家得宝首席信息官。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：家得宝公司</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102516"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/belle-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">林贝儿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-depots-chief-information-officer-on-the-role-of-tech-after-pandemic-sales-boost-7903783d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="">家得宝 (Home Depot)</a>首席信息官法希姆·西迪基 (Fahim Siddiqui <span class="company-name-type">)</span>在这<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-depot-covid-coronavirus-home-improvement-lockdowns-stimulus-check-remodel-11597426959?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">家家居装修零售商的大流行繁荣时期</a>奋战在第一线。在封锁和社交疏远的情况下，顾客涌入其商店——这在许多地方被视为基本服务——并花费巨资装修自己的房屋。</p><p> Siddiqui <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-depot-revamps-tech-leadership-with-focus-on-customers-11650619800" target="_blank" class="icon none">于 2018 年加入家得宝，担任信息技术高级副总裁，并于 2022 年 4 月被任命为家得宝首席信息官</a>。他表示，技术使该零售商的运营得以维持，并强调了早期押注于云计算、人工智能和移动应用程序的重要性。</p><p>现在，随着美国人限制家居装修支出，这家总部位于亚特兰大的零售商的高管警告称， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-depot-hd-q1-earnings-report-2023-56d021?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">年销售额将出现自 2009 年以来的首次下降</a>。5 月份，该连锁店报告收入下降 4.2%，至 372.6 亿美元。</p><p> Siddiqui 在接受《CIO Journal》采访时谈到，技术对于零售商的未来至关重要，因为该公司的目标是扩大承包商和电工等专业客户群，并利用生成式人工智能。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>完整采访的播客可<a href="https://open.spotify.com/episode/3ChuljmXB5PzF1vuY3bNzW?mod=djemCIO" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在此处</a>观看。编辑后的摘录如下：</p><p> <strong>《华尔街日报》：</strong>请向我们介绍一下大流行期间发生的一些事情，以及技术如何帮助您满足客户的需求。</p><p><strong>西迪基：</strong>由于我们和我们的商店都在营业，所以我们也必须始终将我们在网络中看到的流量、我们在供应链中看到的流量、我们在商店中看到的流量联系起来。在那之前我们还没有路边送货服务，我们在几天之内就建立了路边送货功能并将其部署到我们的商店。</p><p>现在，从理论上讲，路边送货听起来相当简单。我下了订单，有人将订单交付给我。但在后端，情况很复杂，因为您必须接受订单，处理订单，将其放入正确的商店，然后在商店内创建工作订单以获取适当的订单，暂存它，当人们这样做时到达后，再次连接它们，让员工将订单交付给该车辆。</p><p>您可以看到有多少东西可能需要跨不同的平台和多个应用程序组合在一起。</p><p> <strong>《华尔街日报》：</strong>家得宝移动应用程序如何推动您对客户的了解，以及如何引导他们找到合适的产品？</p><p> <strong>Siddiqui：</strong>我们将该应用程序视为我们的竞争优势，并为客户提供特定的旅程。如果你往最高层看，我们的DIY客户就占了我们业务的一半，我们的【专业】客户就占了我们业务的一半。</p><p>我们根据DIY客户可能更感兴趣浏览和搜索的需求定制了实际的用户体验。</p><p>我向某人展示该应用程序，我们坐在餐桌旁，餐桌中间有一朵向日葵。所以我拍了一张向日葵的照片，应用程序从我们的库存中找到了所有看起来像向日葵的东西。不幸的是，在这种情况下，它们都是塑料的，但这就是我们在商店出售的。</p><p> <strong>《华尔街日报》：</strong>您如何看待技术在支持业务健康或持续增长方面的作用？</p><p> <strong>Siddiqui：</strong>首先，我们的成长故事真正侧重于构建复杂订单管理、贸易信贷和交付的能力，以满足我们正在寻找计划购买活动的[专业人员]的需求。</p><p>接下来，客户体验。我们在客户体验方面尽了最大努力，但我们也知道，在客户旅程中还有很多机会消除摩擦并成为首选提供商。截至去年，我们将 100% 的设备交付转移到我们的网络（而不是外包给外部配送中心）。我们是否非常擅长并且非常擅长？不。我们相信，在这一情况下我们就有机会。</p><p>我们正在继续并将继续进行适当的技术投资。正如我们所分享的，我们的目标是将 2% 的资本投资于新功能，无论是新商店还是技术。</p><p> <strong>《华尔街日报》：</strong>您个人对零售技术的哪些方面感到兴奋？<br><br> <strong>Siddiqui：</strong>我对生成式人工智能的力量感到非常兴奋，人工智能正在成为我们技术堆栈的核心部分，无论是在浏览、搜索、呼叫中心还是员工手持设备方面。这样他们就可以预见、提高生产力，并真正提供支持和帮助——无论是我们编写的聊天机器人、应用程序还是我们员工手中的设备。</p><p>写信给 Belle Lin： <a href="mailto:belle.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">belle.lin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-depots-chief-information-officer-on-the-role-of-tech-after-pandemic-sales-boost-7903783d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-depots-chief-information-officer-on-the-role-of-tech-after-pandemic-sales-boost-7903783d<author><![CDATA[Belle Lin]]></author><category>人工智能技术</category><category>零售批发</category><category>家居用品零售</category><category>装饰/DIY/五金零售</category><category>专业零售</category><category>伊泰林</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>零售</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>管理</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>家园改造</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>家居与园艺</category><category>家得宝</category><category>高清</category><category>法希姆·西迪基</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>管理</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>家园改造</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>家居与花园</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>家庭用品零售</category><category>装饰</category><category>DIY</category><category>五金零售</category><category>专业零售</category><category>电子邮寄</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Memory Chip Nightmare is Nearly Over]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>低端价格仍在下跌，但三星和 SK 海力士的业绩强烈暗示未来会更好<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103922"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828115?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">有迹象表明，存储芯片的库存状况终于开始改善。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jakub Porzycki/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103922"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jacky-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">黄学友</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 8:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-memory-chip-nightmare-is-nearly-over-e4e571e6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>投资者可能很快就会开始忘记——或者至少消除——存储芯片股票糟糕的一年所带来的创伤。</p><p>韩国芯片制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SSNHZ" class="company-name">三星</a>电子和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/000660" class="company-name">SK 海力士</a>上周均公布了截至 6 月的季度业绩。但这两家公司也给投资者带来了一线希望，即最糟糕的时期已经过去。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828122?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>三星<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/samsung-electronics-second-quarter-net-profit-fell-84-above-consensus-cb45eb19?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">第二季度营收同比下降 22%</a> ，营业利润暴跌 95%。海力士的销售额较上年同期几乎减少一半，亏损较上一季度扩大。大流行时代电子产品繁荣的幽灵仍然困扰着芯片制造商：主要表现为供应链上潜藏的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chip-shortages-might-finally-ease-for-asia-thats-a-mixed-bag-11654167612?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量库存</a>。据摩根士丹利称，2023 年第一季度全球供应链（包括制造商、分销商和客户）的芯片库存总量为 258 天，比历史中位数高出 76 天。</p><p>但有迹象表明，存储芯片的库存状况终于开始改善。三星表示，其库存在五月份达到顶峰。与上一季度相比，海力士上季度的库存天数有所下降。</p><p>部分原因是制造商大幅减产，尤其是三星，它在价格暴跌之初<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-samsung-could-climb-out-of-the-chip-price-pit-11672998250?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">并不愿意这样做</a>。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="company-name">高盛</a>估计，三星已将用于处理的 DRAM 和用于存储的 NAND 的产量削减了约 20% 至 25%。该银行预计三星将进一步削减 NAND 产量 5% 至 10%。这已经开始支撑价格，尤其是 DRAM。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=51099F5C-C981-4E8B-ADCA-0F740EF859FD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-memory-chip-nightmare-is-nearly-over-e4e571e6&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">价值 530 亿美元的《芯片法案》旨在结束美国对外国制造半导体的依赖，特别是五角大楼使用的半导体。这是联邦政府利用资金重塑其认为对国家安全至关重要的行业的最新例子。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>人工智能应用的需求也正在成为真正的亮点。由于人工智能服务器使用的优质产品的更好组合，海力士上季度 DRAM 的平均售价实际上有所上涨。其中包括高带宽内存芯片，可提供更快的数据传输。该公司是该领域的领导者：它是第一家大规模生产最新一代芯片的公司。海力士预计其人工智能服务器内存收入将比去年同期增长一倍以上。</p><p>然而，股价可能已经在很大程度上体现了这种乐观的前景。三星的股价今年上涨了 26%，而海力士的股价则飙升了 59%，这反映出后者对快速增长的人工智能需求的敞口更大。</p><p>对于大多数芯片行业投资者来说，2021 年和 2022 年初的繁荣时期已经成为遥远的记忆。好时光还没有到来，但随着库存最终被削减，人工智能提高了高端产品的利润率，本次下行周期中最糟糕的情况可能终于成为过去。</p><p>写信给 Jacky Wong： <a href="mailto:jacky.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jacky.wong@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 12:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-memory-chip-nightmare-is-nearly-over-e4e571e6</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-memory-chip-nightmare-is-nearly-over-e4e571e6<author><![CDATA[Jacky Wong]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>半导体</category><category>音视频设备</category><category>消费品</category><category>耐用家居产品</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>家用电子/电器</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> SK海力士</category><category>000660.SE</category><category>韩国：000660</category><category>三星电子</category><category>005930.SE</category><category> KR:005930</category><category>三星</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>半导体</category><category>声音的</category><category>视频设备</category><category>消费品</category><category>耐用家用产品</category><category>家用电子产品</category><category>电器</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Don’t Fly Without These Five Travel Apps]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>面对当今的旅行挑战时，拥有一部提供额外帮助的智能手机是值得的<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826945/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图<span>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001099069"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001099069"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dawn-gilbertson"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-548480" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dawn-gilbertson" itemprop="url" rel="author">道恩·吉尔伯特森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-fly-without-these-five-travel-apps-b17b0755"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>无论您是偶尔与家人度假还是实际居住在机场，没有什么比可靠的应用程序更能帮助您的旅行更加顺利了。</p><p>任何旅行应用程序都无法帮助您避免航班取消、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/airport-security-tsa-wait-times-b49eec89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">运输安全管理局 (TSA) 排队</a>和其他麻烦。但是，掌握实时数据可以帮助您更快地行动，并在出现旅行问题时为您提供更好的选择。</p><p>我们都相当依赖航空公司和酒店应用程序，这些应用程序通常与忠诚度计划挂钩。我询问了几位旅游高管、航空极客和最常乘坐飞机的人，请他们告诉我他们还依赖哪些<em>其他</em>应用程序来保持出行。</p><p>以下是他们的建议：</p><h3>旅行组织</h3><p>来自企业旅行预订和费用管理公司 SAP Concur 的<a href="https://www.tripit.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none"><strong>TripIt</strong></a>是我的非科学调查中的大赢家。有一个免费版本，可以根据确认电子邮件或您手动输入的有关航班、酒店和度假租赁、汽车租赁、火车等的信息来构建您的旅行行程。每年 49 美元的 TripIt Pro 订阅增加了航班提醒，并可以跟踪票价、座位可用性变化、忠诚度积分等。</p><p> Chuck Stapleton 住在佛罗里达州奥兰多，从事国防工业信息技术工作，他说他在出差和度假时经常使用 TripIt。 “他们基本上会为你制定一个行程，”他说。 “这对于我的旅行中有很多令人感动的事情非常有帮助。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d1b7ab61-8fab-4fb1-a9b3-2822aaf83a08.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>斯台普顿说，他一眼就能看出行程中是否有漏洞。几年前去瑞士之前，他查看了应用程序，并没有看到酒店列表中的酒店。这帮助他意识到自己预订了错误的日期，并让他有时间在旅行前纠正路线。</p><p>专业之旅：如果您的公司使用 SAP Concur（像我的公司一样）， <a href="https://help.tripit.com/en/support/solutions/articles/103000063274-sap-concur-getting-started-with-tripit" target="_blank" class="icon none">您可以链接您的帐户</a>，甚至可能免费获得 TripIt Pro。您可以<a href="https://help.tripit.com/en/support/solutions/articles/103000063370-sap-concur-personal-and-business-trips" target="_blank" class="icon none">选择是否将个人行程同步</a>到您的公司 Concur 帐户。</p><h3>航班追踪</h3><p>罗斯·范斯坦 (Ross Feinstein) 是一名曾在美国航空公司和运输安全管理局工作的顾问，他的手机上有十几个装满旅行应用程序的文件夹。一个文件夹包含 11 个不同的航班跟踪器。</p><p> <a href="https://www.flightyapp.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none"><strong>Flighty</strong></a>是他的新宠。它于 2019 年推出， <a href="https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2023/06/apple-announces-winners-of-the-2023-apple-design-awards/" target="_blank" class="icon none">今年赢得了苹果设计奖的</a>交互类别，该奖项奖励那些提供“直观界面和轻松控制”的软件。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f1c43128-d441-4747-ab14-6c037c9e59fd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>该应用程序的免费版本适用于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a>设备，下个月将支持 Apple Watch，让您可以跟踪无限数量的航班状态。</p><p>每年 49 美元的 Flighty Pro 包含该服务的出色功能，包括日历同步以及有关延误、取消和登机口变更的快速推送通知。 Feinstein 是一名铁杆航空迷，对该应用程序对飞机尾号的跟踪印象最深刻。通过监控进港飞机的状态，该应用程序可以在航空公司通知用户之前通知用户其出港航班可能出现故障。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您最喜欢的旅行应用程序是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>周日，范斯坦预订了上午 9:30 从达拉斯/沃斯堡飞往纽约的航班。中午12点30分，Flighty提醒他，入境航班延误了五个小时。达美航空直到凌晨 3 点才提醒他自己的航班延误了 5 个小时</p><p>由于飞机调换，进港航班迟到并不总是意味着类似的出港航班延误。此外，如果您仔细挖掘，还可以在许多航空公司应用程序中找到这些信息。但范斯坦表示，早期的提醒让他找到了更快回家的路。</p><h3>最后一刻的酒店房间</h3><p>卡内基梅隆大学 (Carnegie Mellon University) 教授 Po-Shen Loh 今年夏天将前往 64 个城市执行一项<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-math-po-shen-loh-1e9f80dc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">疯狂的任务</a>，他为了省钱而采取了老派的做法。他最喜欢的应用程序： <a href="https://www.hotwire.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none"><strong>Hotwire</strong></a> ，该应用程序已为旅行者提供了二十多年的服务，隶属于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/EXPE" class="">Expedia Group</a> <span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p> Loh 专门预订 Hotwire 的热门房价，您可以在预订前了解酒店的位置、一般设施和星级，但不知道酒店名称。有趣的事实：该公司表示，应用程序中的价格比网站上的价格便宜。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/5d4af5bb-1475-48bf-9e16-04c5948c8516.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>上周，他在最后一刻以每晚100美元的价格预订了达拉斯一家评价很高的酒店。</p><p> Hotwire 房价不可退款，也不符合连锁酒店忠诚度积分的资格。这位数学家表示，他并没有相信酒店忠诚度与他所珍视的航空公司忠诚度的价值。</p><p> “对我来说，升级的房间与[美联航]北极星商务舱的价值不一样，”他说。</p><h3>天气</h3><p>天气应用程序的推荐并不缺乏，但其中有一款脱颖而出。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JBLU" class="">捷蓝航空 (JetBlue Airways)</a>首席数字和技术官卡罗尔·克莱门茨 (Carol Clements) 是<a href="https://www.tomorrow.io/consumer-app/" target="_blank" class="icon none"><strong>Tomorrow.io</strong></a>的粉丝<span class="company-name-type">，</span>这是一款免费应用程序，以前称为 ClimaCell。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/99d02c4d-aaa2-4a8e-af9d-979e82174e08.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>克莱门茨说，当该应用程序开发商的早期投资者捷蓝航空将天气预报技术添加到其位于纽约的运营中心时，她就被介绍给了该应用程序。她今年早些时候开始亲自使用它。她发现预测准确且功能很有帮助。</p><p> “你可以突出显示跑步、远足、骑自行车等活动作为爱好，”她说，“应用程序会告诉你每天进行该活动的最佳时间。”</p><h3>使用机场休息室</h3><p><a href="https://www.loungebuddy.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none"><strong>LoungeBuddy</strong></a>是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-express-airport-lounges-cut-back-on-free-plus-ones-44177f17?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国运通公司旗下</a>一款仅限 iOS 的应用程序，得到了 Feinstein 和 Loh 的认可。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/9c376157-16c4-4a9e-9445-6e50ec34b26d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>这款免费应用程序会告诉旅客他们是否可以使用特定机场的休息室，并告诉他们可以在哪里购买一日通行证。您还可以找到休息室评论。</p><p> Loh 喜欢通过便利设施进行搜索的功能。他最想要的福利是：淋浴。</p><p> <em>—订阅新的</em><a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=494&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>《华尔街日报》旅游通讯，</em></a><em>了解 Dawn Gilbertson 和《华尔街日报》旅游团队其他成员的更多提示和见解。</em></p><p>写信给道恩·吉尔伯特森： <a href="mailto:dawn.gilbertson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dawn.gilbertson@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-fly-without-these- Five-travel-apps-b17b0755</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-fly-without-these- Five-travel-apps-b17b0755<author><![CDATA[Dawn Gilbertson]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>住宿/餐厅/酒吧</category><category>住宿</category><category>酒店/汽车旅馆</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>租赁服务</category><category>乘用车租赁/租赁</category><category>航空运输</category><category>道路车辆租赁/租赁</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>计算</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>移动应用软件</category><category>技术</category><category>旅游</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>产品/服务中断</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>旅行</category><category>旅游评论</category><category>天气</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>产品</category><category>服务中断</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>旅行</category><category>旅行评论</category><category>天气</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>住宿</category><category>餐馆</category><category>酒吧</category><category>酒店</category><category>汽车旅馆</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>出租</category><category>租赁服务</category><category>客车租赁</category><category>租赁</category><category>航空运输</category><category>公路车辆租赁</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>计算</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category><category>移动应用软件</category><category>技术</category><category>旅游</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AI-Generated Data Could Be a Boon for Healthcare—If Only It Seemed More Real]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>人工智能使研究人员能够从患者数据集中编织“合成数据”。但首席信息官质疑生成的数据是否足以捕获对研究有用的医疗变量<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098858"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827019?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">强生公司的员工在公司位于加利福尼亚州欧文市的实验室进行协作。该公司看到了使用合成数据进行研究的潜力，但表示该技术仍需要成熟。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：强生公司</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098858"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/isabelle-bousquette" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊莎贝尔·布斯克特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-generated-data-could-be-a-boon-for-healthcareif-only-it-seemed-more-real-5bfe52dd"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>医疗保健公司对“合成数据”的可能性着迷，“合成数据”是通过将人工智能算法应用于真实数据集而构建的数据。但持续存在的技术挑战继续限制行业的广泛采用，许多公司不愿使用它。</p><p>多年来，药物和健康研究人员一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-people-in-this-medical-research-are-fake-the-innovations-are-real-11617717623?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在试验</a>这项技术，这使他们能够更自由地分析药物对特定亚群的影响，而无需遇到典型的隐私和监管障碍。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IT" class="company-name">Gartner</a> 2021 年的一项研究估计，到明年，广泛用于人工智能和分析项目开发的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fake-it-to-make-it-companies-beef-up-ai-models-with-synthetic-data-11627032601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数据中 60%</a>将是综合生成的。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> IT 研究和咨询公司的分析师阿伦·钱德拉塞卡兰 (Arun Chandrasekaran) 澄清说，现实远非如此。他说，在某些领域，产生的数据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fake-it-to-make-it-companies-beef-up-ai-models-with-synthetic-data-11627032601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已经取得了进展</a>，例如，作为训练自动驾驶汽车的图像。但在健康和药物研究中，合成数据对于生成医疗记录特别有用，但采用率仍然很低。</p><p>该技术高昂的成本和供应商数量稀少一直拖累其采用。但医疗保健公司表示，更大的问题是确保合成数据准确代表目标人群，换句话说，更像真实数据。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JNJ" class="">强生公司首席信息官吉姆·</a>斯旺森 (Jim Swanson) 表示：“医疗保健和科学领域的复杂性和多变性使其成为一个非常难以解决的问题<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ”</p><p>斯旺森认为有前景的领域之一是分析市场上已有药物的长期影响和有效性。目前，该公司使用去识别化的患者数据来实现这一点，这些数据中的标识符已被删除或更改，但可以通过其他详细信息链接回该人。 （理论上，匿名数据会去除所有可识别信息。）该公司表示，合成数据可以创建更大的数据集，包括在数据限制严格的领域。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826796?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">华尔街地区的纽约长老会医院。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>但斯旺森说，考虑到患者存在许多相关变量：他们服用了多少药物、是否吸烟、是否需要髋关节置换术等等，创建一个具有代表性的数据集很困难。他补充说，随着新的科学发现的出现，这些变量可能会发生变化。与此同时，原始数据中变量的混合和构成必须在合成数据顺序中得到公平捕获，以进行准确的分析。</p><p> “你可以很容易地创建合成数据，但它的相关性是否足以为你提供一个具体而准确的例子？”斯旺森说道。 “这就是你必须解决的问题。”</p><p>麻省理工学院计算机科学与人工智能实验室首席研究科学家 Lalana Kagal 表示，在创建合成数据时，需要在准确性和隐私之间进行权衡。通常，合成数据是通过人工智能算法运行真实数据来创建的，该算法以相似但不相同的形式重新创建数据。合成数据越接近原始源数据，就越准确，但也更有可能泄露原始数据。此外，她表示，目前还不清楚合成数据必须与源数据有多相似才能遵守 HIPAA 法律。 《健康保险流通与责任法案》保护健康记录。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您如何看待在医学研究中使用合成数据？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> It&#39;s possible new techniques could be developed to ensure the original data stays private without sacrificing the accuracy of the synthetic data, Kagal said. In the meantime, some companies are hanging back.</p><p> In 2021, genomics company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ILMN" class="company-name">Illumina</a> published a promising case study on the use of synthetic data in genomics with technology vendor Gretel. More recently, however, Illumina said synthetic data isn&#39;t a priority in research and development at the company.</p><p> At NewYork-Presbyterian, Peter Fleischut, chief information and transformation officer, said he&#39;s more focused on ensuring there are strong enough cybersecurity and privacy systems in place to use real data. He is following developments around synthetic data, he said, but it&#39;s not something the medical center has experimented much with.</p><p> “If we&#39;re creating a heart-failure algorithm, we really think that those algorithms should be based on actual data and patients that represent the patients that we serve,” Fleischut said. With synthetic data, “I have not yet been convinced that it&#39;s truly representative of the patients we serve.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> “You can create synthetic data easily enough, but is it correlated enough to give you a specific and an accurate example? That&#39;s the problem you have to solve.” <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p> <small><span class="inset-author article__inset__pullquote__author">— Jim Swanson, J&amp;J</span></small></div></div><p> Yet another difficulty is the fledgling vendor market, said Gartner&#39;s Chandrasekaran. Gartner is tracking just over two dozen vendors, but most are startups, founded in the last four to five years. The major cloud providers, which businesses are generally more comfortable working with, have largely stayed out of the market, he said. They might be tempted in once there&#39;s more demand, but it&#39;s hard to generate that demand without them already in the market, he said, calling it “sort of a chicken and egg.”</p><p> The health sector&#39;s reticence might be overcome as the technology matures.</p><p> Swanson said, “We&#39;re excited about its potential.”</p><p> Write to Isabelle Bousquette at <a href="mailto:isabelle.bousquette@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">isabelle.bousquette@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-generated-data-could-be-a-boon-for-healthcareif-only-it-seemed-more-real-5bfe52dd</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-generated-data-could-be-a-boon-for-healthcareif-only-it-seemed-more-real-5bfe52dd<author><![CDATA[Isabelle Bousquette]]></author><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>Healthcare Information Technologies</category><category>技术</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>隐私问题/信息安全</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>隐私问题</category><category>信息安全</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>healthcare information technologies</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘How Do I Do That?’ The New Hires of 2023 Are Unprepared for Work]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Remote learning during the pandemic left students short of basic skills. Now companies are trying to teach them on the job. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827972/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="密歇根州大急流城约翰·鲍尔动物园的售票处。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The ticket office of the John Ball Zoo in Grand Rapids, Mich. Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal <span>Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101284"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101284"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/douglas-belkin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Douglas Belkin</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ben-chapman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ben Chapman</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ben-kesling" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ben Kesling</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Roman Devengenzo was consulting for a robotics company in Silicon Valley last fall when he asked a newly minted mechanical engineer to design a small aluminum part that could be fabricated on a lathe—a skill normally mastered in the first or second year of college.</p><p> “How do I do that?” asked the young man.</p><p> So Devengenzo, an engineer who has built technology for NASA and Google, and who charges consulting clients a minimum of $300 an hour, spent the next three hours teaching Lathework 101. “You learn by doing,” he said. “These kids in school during the pandemic, all they&#39;ve done is work on computers.”</p><p>疫情期间多年的远程学习所产生的连锁反应正在使全国各地的工作场所陷入困境。这是专业服务职位空缺和商品无法进入市场的原因之一。 It also helps explain why national productivity has fallen for the past five quarters, the longest contraction since at least 1948, according to the US Labor Department.</p><p> The shortcomings run the gamut from general knowledge, including how to make change at a register, to soft skills such as working with others. Employers are spending more time and resources searching for candidates and often lowering expectations when they hire.然后，他们花费数百万美元来解决新员工缺乏基本技能的问题。</p><p>位于密歇根州大急流城的一个以企业为主导的劳动力发展组织 Talent First 正在鼓励雇主停止尝试根据技能进行招聘。相反，招聘经理应该寻找学习的意愿，总裁凯文·斯托茨说。</p><p> “雇主们说，‘我们只是想找到一些能让镜子起雾的人，’”斯托茨说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828009?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自2020年疫情爆发、远程学习让学生走出学校进入虚拟教室以来，工程师、上班族、士兵和护士参加的国家认证和评估考试的通过率均有所下降。</p><p> Among the approximately 40,000 candidates taking the Fundamentals of Engineering exam for work as professional engineers, scores fell by about 10% during the pandemic, said David Cox, CEO of the National Council of Examiners for Engineering and Surveying.</p><p> That means fewer engineers on the job and a lower degree of competency among those who make it, he said.</p><p> The sharpest declines in scores came on questions measuring the most specialized knowledge. Structural engineers failed to answer questions about the use of trusses in the construction of bridges and roadways, Cox said.</p><p> “These are areas that are very much involved in public safety,” he said.</p><p> Students in elementary and middle schools across the nation fell behind by an average of about four months during the pandemic after classes switched to remote learning in 2019 and stayed that way in some cases through 2021. On national <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/education-departments-first-pandemic-era-trend-data-show-worst-reading-math-declines-in-decades-11662004860?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">standardized tests</a> , the scores of fourth- and eighth-graders fell to 30-year lows.</p><p> Students who were in high-school and college when Covid-19 hit and are now entering the workforce didn&#39;t fare much better. Despite lowered standards at many schools during the pandemic, <a href="https://www.chalkbeat.org/2022/1/24/22895461/2021-graduation-rates-decrease-pandemic" target="_blank" class="icon none">high-school graduation rates fell</a> . Scores for college admissions exams dropped <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/act-test-scores-drop-to-lowest-levels-in-more-than-30-years-11665593614?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to the lowest level in three decades</a> .</p><p> Janet Godwin, chief executive of ACT, the nonprofit organization which administers the college admission test of the same name, said more high-school graduates today lack the fundamental academic skills needed for college and the workplace, with low-performing students facing the steepest declines.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>In what ways have people in your workplace needed extra support and skill-building since the pandemic? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> In Covid-19&#39;s aftermath, many college professors restructured curricula for students who lack basic study skills.</p><p> “Reading, writing and critical-thinking skills are not the same as they were in the past,” said Mike Altman, a religion professor at the University of Alabama who said he has narrowed his curriculum to give his students more time to master basics.</p><p> During the pandemic more than 100,000 nurses left the field, <a href="https://www.healthaffairs.org/do/10.1377/forefront.20220412.311784/" target="_blank" class="icon none">the largest decline in four decades of available data,</a> a study in the journal Health Affairs showed. That has placed tremendous strain on hospitals and increased demands on programs to graduate more nurses. But students taking entrance exams to study nursing are scoring an average of about 5 percentage points lower than before the pandemic, limiting the number of students eligible to enroll in nursing programs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=839822A9-3A5F-4A5D-9390-E94EDF4A2336&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">人工智能在白领工作中发挥着越来越重要的作用，能够起草电子邮件、演示文稿、图像等。工人们已经因为科技而失去了工作，一些首席执行官正在改变未来的招聘计划。 《华尔街日报》解释道。插图：雅各布·雷诺兹<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>More students who do enroll struggle to earn passing grades, said Patty Knecht, Vice President of Ascend Learning Healthcare, a private company which helps train medical professionals. And even if they do graduate, more are struggling to pass a certification exam. By then, they may already be on the payroll but unable to work. The delays cost hospitals an average of $42,000 per student who fails the certification exam, said Knecht.</p><p> Last year, Ivy Tech Community College, the largest nursing program in Indiana, embedded tutors in classrooms to assist lagging students with skills they should have mastered in high school. Some of the most basic included the math necessary to figure out correct dosages for medicine.</p><p> Joseph Mulumba, who is about to start his sophomore year in the Ivy Tech nursing program, was a high-school sophomore in Indiana when the pandemic arrived. His school was remote for a year.</p><p> “I feel like I would have learned a lot more if not for the pandemic, “ Mulumba said. “When I got here I realized I wasn&#39;t ready for nursing school. I realized I didn&#39;t know how to study.”</p><p> Jerrica Moses, national recruitment manager for Senture, a London, Ky.-based call-center company, says new workers have problems with soft skills, such as an inability to deal with frustration. Senture, which employs about 4,200 customer-service representatives, has adopted a new set of tests to determine which prospective employees will be able to keep their cool under stress from angry or rude callers.</p><p> “Candidates who wash out respond by explaining how aggravated they get with the callers and then focus on the stress,” said Moses. Most of the people who struggle are under 25 years old, she added. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="842" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827911?width=1260&amp;height=842" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ivan Schury, 17, helps cook on the line at the John Ball Zoo&#39;s Monkey Island Cafe.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In Grand Rapids, managers at the John Ball Zoo are coaching seasonal workers in their teens and early 20s on basics such as why it&#39;s important to look visitors in the eye, and how to make change at a cash register.</p><p> They are also trying to instill a work ethic in their employees that includes taking some initiative, getting off their phones and engaging with visitors, said Laura Davis, the director of strategy and organizational development at the zoo. Her young employees haven&#39;t been held accountable for things like finishing homework assignments, and Davis believes that has led to a decline in motivation.</p><p> “They&#39;re not looking to be productive,” Davis said. “If they&#39;re not told what to do, if someone isn&#39;t managing every second and keeping them busy, their inclination is not to self identify what they can do—it&#39;s to do nothing.”</p><p> The pandemic arrived when Ivan Schury was in the eighth grade. Now 17 years old and a supervisor in the zoo&#39;s kitchen, he said the isolation he and his peers experienced over the next few years have left many distracted and disengaged.</p><p> Last week a teenager working the fry station kept wandering off. “He just kept walking away to talk to his friends at the counter,” Schury said. “I spend a lot of time making sure people stay on task.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827910?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Charity Fields, age 19, stands inside the gift shop of the John Ball Zoo.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Charity Fields, 19 years old, works in the gift shop and says she is frequently surprised by the lack of motivation of her younger co-workers. A few days ago a 16-year-old fellow sales associate sat in a chair reading a book while customers shopped.</p><p> “I told her we weren&#39;t really supposed to do that,” Fields said. The girl got up, stood near the cash register, leaned on the counter and continued to read.</p><p> The problem extends to the US military, exacerbating <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/military-recruiting-crisis-veterans-dont-want-their-children-to-join-510e1a25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pressures the services face from poor recruiting</a> .</p><p> Army recruits aren&#39;t communicating within their squads as well as they did before  the pandemic, instructors say. Scores on recruiting exams fell 9% since the pandemic and prompted the Army to create a new testing boot camp to help recruits pass, a requirement for gaining admission to the military.</p><p> Army Secretary Christine Wormuth believes a lot of the struggles are tied into isolation that took root when students learned remotely during the pandemic.</p><p> “So many young people spent two years in relative isolation and not doing a lot of group projects,” she said.</p><p> Young workers&#39; struggles have become vividly apparent to Criteria Corp, a Los Angeles company that administers about 10 million assessments a year to evaluate prospective employees. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827523?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> New soldiers at Ft. Moore in Georgia are drilled in test-taking skills, including deep-breathing exercises, so they can perform better on the Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery, or ASVAB.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Walter Banks for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Results for test takers overall have held steady with a notable decline in the scores of men between 18 and 24 and usually with a high-school education, said Josh Millet, co-founder and CEO of the company.</p><p> The company&#39;s Criteria Basic Skills Test measures reading comprehension, verbal skills and numeracy. Companies use it to hire for positions such as administrative assistants, customer-service representatives, medical assistants, insurance salespeople and bank tellers. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Men under 25 struggled with the verbal section of this standardized test</h4><p> <em>Which of the following sentences contains an error?</em></p><p> A. Halfway there, they ran out of fuel.</p><p> B. They began practice their piano duet.</p><p> C. This book is about sea creatures.</p><p> D. His business partner agreed to meet with him.</p><p> <em>Choose the word that completes the sentence correctly.</em></p><p> Denise thought working with a reporter would be exciting, but she had answered the same question several times and was beginning to find the interview_________.</p><p> A. unique</p><p> B. repugnant</p><p> C. exhilarating</p><p> D. tedious</p><p> E. satisfying</p><p> Source: Criteria Basic Skills Test</p></div></div><p> Verbal scores for men under 25 declined by 11 percentage points over the three years of the pandemic. Scores for women were less dramatically affected. The biggest dips among men were registered in communication skills, reading comprehension, grammar, spelling and attention to detail, said Millet.</p><p> “Our customers consistently tell us that finding high-quality candidates is the single greatest challenge to the successful execution of their talent strategies, and it seems that diminished educational outcomes may exacerbate that challenge,” Millet said.</p><p> Cindy Neal, owner of Express Employment Professionals in Peoria, Ill., places about 1,500 people in jobs every year. Since the pandemic, she has seen sharp declines in the behavior of job applicants as well as their performance on employment exams.</p><p> The company has long offered courses for people to gain new skills such as QuickBooks. This spring they added new courses to help prospective workers with soft skills. Some of the chapters taught include taking initiative, personal productivity, cellphone etiquette, workplace hygiene, dressing appropriately for work and handling conflict with co-workers.</p><p> “This stuff used to be taught in schools,” Neal said. “Now people have to be told not to bring their kids to work.”</p><p> Results on the 15-minute employment exam the company administers to clients when they walk in the door are also declining.</p><p> Tasks on the quiz include recognizing misspellings in words like “availability,” “repetition” and “privilege,” and math questions such as: “If you were asked to load 225 boxes onto a truck and the boxes are crated, with each crate containing nine boxes, how many crates would you need to load?”</p><p> The scores in math and spelling are the worst she&#39;s seen in 30 years, she said, adding, “I&#39;m really concerned by the product that&#39;s coming out of the school system currently.”</p><p> Write to Douglas Belkin at <a href="mailto:Doug.Belkin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Doug.Belkin@wsj.com</a> , Ben Chapman at <a href="mailto:ben.chapman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ben.chapman@wsj.com</a> and Ben Kesling at <a href="mailto:ben.kesling@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ben.kesling@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33<author><![CDATA[Douglas BelkinBen ChapmanBen Kesling]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category>领导者</category><category>wsj-usnews</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>招聘</category><category>Work-Life Balance</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>健康</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category> School</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>Telecommuting</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Career Education</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>recruitment</category><category> work-life balance</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>健康</category><category>general labor issues</category><category> living</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>outbreaks</category><category>流行病</category><category>学校</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>telecommuting</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>career education </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Toyota’s Land Cruiser to Return to U.S.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Carmaker announces new version of off-roading SUV that aims to compete with Jeep and Ford Bronco <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103297"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828039?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Toyota&#39;s new Land Cruiser made its debut in Tokyo, and could be back in North America next year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Akio Kon/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103297"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/river-davis" itemprop="url" rel="author">River Davis</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 2, 2023 4:27 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyotas-land-cruiser-to-return-to-the-u-s-7b2eb343"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><br> TOKYO— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TM" class="company-name">Toyota</a> Motor is bringing a long-running icon of off-roading back to the US</p><p> At an event in Tokyo on Wednesday, Toyota showed off a new Land Cruiser, reminiscent of boxy pre-2000s versions of the sport-utility vehicle. The company said it plans to bring the new vehicle to the US next year, two years after discontinuing the Land Cruiser in that market.</p><p> The move resembles <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-to-reveal-new-bronco-after-24-years-off-the-market-11594667167" target="_blank" class="icon none">Ford&#39;s decision in 2020 to relaunch</a> its previously discontinued off-roading SUV, the Bronco.</p><p> Like the Bronco, the new Land Cruiser could put <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jeep-looks-to-veer-out-of-sales-ditch-74ba0a58?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">further pressure</a> on rival Jeep&#39;s position in the “adventure vehicle” category. Car companies in recent years have been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/suvs-are-bumper-to-bumper-on-dealer-lots-with-more-on-the-way-11562491801?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">crowding showrooms</a> with new versions of SUVs and other big, higher-profit vehicles. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827261?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The Land Cruiser discontinued in the US in 2021 hadn&#39;t received a major update in years. Starting at upward of $80,000, it struggled to compete in the high-price segment, though it retained a following among some off-road enthusiasts.</p><p> The US price of the new Land Cruiser will start in the mid-$50,000s.</p><p> Toyota is marketing the new model as an SUV for people who actually drive off-road, rather than just daydreaming about it. “At the heart of this is reliability and durability and performance over rough terrain,” said Chief Branding Officer Simon Humphries. He called it “proud to be raw and utilitarian.”</p><p> Humphries said the company welcomes competition from off-roading-SUV rivals. “It&#39;s like a sports car—there are Land Cruiser guys and there are Bronco guys. Everyone has their own preference,” he said.</p><p> The new Land Cruiser will go on sale next year in the US as a hybrid vehicle, underscoring Toyota&#39;s resolve to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyota-pitches-a-new-prius-as-plug-in-hybrids-battle-evs-for-share-31785660?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">continue making gasoline-electric cars</a> even as more customers choose fully battery-powered models.</p><p> Toyota introduced the Land Cruiser in the 1950s for what was then known as Japan&#39;s National Police Reserve, a predecessor to today&#39;s Ground Self Defense Force—that is, the army. Its name was a nod to Britain&#39;s Land Rover.</p><p> Through the years, the Land Cruiser became popular in places with rough terrain such as Australia and the Middle East. Icelandic glaciers, Australian underground mines and other locales with extreme conditions are a staple of Toyota promotions. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828040?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Toyota&#39;s chief branding officer, Simon Humphries, said the new Land Cruiser is &#39;proud to be raw and utilitarian.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Akio Kon/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The company said that as of June 2023 it had sold 11.3 million Land Cruiser models globally over the years.</p><p> Its moment in the sun in the US came around the turn of the century, when Americans were buying more than 15,000 Land Cruisers annually. By the time it was discontinued in 2021, annual sales had dwindled to just a few thousand units, less than 1% of sales of Toyota&#39;s RAV4 SUV.</p><p> The new Land Cruiser has high-mounted headlights and a simple, angular structure. Humphries said the design had evolved naturally in a direction that recalled older models because the priority was functionality. Some recent Land Cruiser models had aimed for more of a luxury feel.</p><p> Write to River Davis at <a href="mailto:river.davis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">river.davis@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 08:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyotas-land-cruiser-to-return-to-the-us-7b2eb343</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyotas-land-cruiser-to-return-to-the-us-7b2eb343<author><![CDATA[River Davis]]></author><category>机动车</category><category>Passenger Cars</category><category> Sports Utility Vehicles</category><category>汽车</category><category>New Products/Services</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Toyota Motor</category><category> 7203.TO</category><category> JP:7203</category><category> new products</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>机动车</category><category>passenger cars</category><category> sports utility vehicles</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Crypto Is Illegal in China. Binance Does $90 Billion of Business There Anyway.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>由于币安面临全球监管打压，保留其在中国的足迹对于币安来说至关重要<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827745/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>亚历山德拉·西特林-萨法迪/《华尔街日报》；照片：iStock <span>Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/《华尔街日报》；照片：iStock</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101337"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101337"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/patricia-kowsmann" itemprop="url" rel="author">帕特里夏·考斯曼</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/caitlin-ostroff" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯特琳·奥斯特罗夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-is-illegal-in-china-binance-does-90-billion-of-business-there-anyway-2a0af975"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>当中国在 2021 年将加密货币交易定为非法时， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/binance-became-the-biggest-cryptocurrency-exchange-without-licenses-or-headquarters-thats-coming-to-an-end-11636640029?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球最大的加密货币交易所</a>币安本应将中国抛在后面。</p><p>根据《华尔街日报》以及现任和前任员工查看的内部数据，近两年后，中国用户在一个月内交易了 900 亿美元的加密货币相关资产。这些交易使中国币安成为迄今为止最大的市场，占全球交易量的 20%（不包括部分超大型交易商的交易）。</p><p>据现任和前任员工称，中国对币安的重要性在内部进行了公开讨论。据一些现任和前任员工称，尽管有禁令，该交易所的调查团队仍与中国执法部门密切合作，以侦查该国超过 90 万活跃用户中潜在的犯罪活动。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827969?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>币安正面临监管冲击，部分原因在于其在全球范围内的秘密运营方式。美国证券交易委员会于 6 月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-binance-ceo-operates-weigh-the-risk-calculate-the-reward-fa427f7f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">起诉币安及其创始人</a>赵长鹏，指控其非法经营和滥用客户资金。司法部正在对币安进行持续调查。它在美国用户中的市场份额<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-binance-us-crypto-trading-was-a-mirage-the-sec-alleges-55a6e321" target="_blank" class="icon none">几乎消失殆尽</a>，而且该公司最近在全球<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/binance-lays-off-over-1-000-employees-d59ff6ad" target="_blank" class="icon none">8,000 个岗位中裁掉了 1,000 多个岗位</a>。</p><p>币安在中国的足迹此前并未公开，这让我们得以一睹这家加密巨头如何在不受欢迎的地方悄悄地在边缘运作，至少在官方层面上是这样。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》看到的一份列出程序的内部文件显示，币安通过引导中国用户访问具有中文域名的不同网站，然后将其重新路由到全球交易所来帮助中国用户规避限制。该文件在 2021 年禁令之前、但在中国于 2017 年封锁该交易所网站之后在该公司内部流传。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-declares-bitcoin-and-other-cryptocurrency-transactions-illegal-11632479288" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">实施加密货币禁令的</a>中国央行没有回应置评请求。</p><p> “Binance.com 网站在中国被屏蔽，中国用户无法访问，”该公司发言人表示，但没有进一步置评。</p><p>币安在全球处理的加密货币交易数量超过了大多数竞争对手的总和。对于币安来说，保持在中国的足迹至关重要，因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/binance-unravels-as-executives-flee-and-layoffs-proliferate-4c49b6d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">高管们内部担心</a>监管打压会威胁到币安的未来。</p><p>币安与中国的关系很复杂。出生于中国、在加拿大长大的赵先生于 2017 年在上海创立了这家公司。几个月后，政府发布了针对加密货币交易所的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-to-shut-bitcoin-exchanges-sources-1505100862" target="_blank" class="icon none">多项滚动监管攻击中的第一个</a>。官员们担心这些交易所将被用来将资金非法转移出该国。赵后来说，他将币安的业务转移到了日本。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=995FCADF-1BFE-4730-BAF7-D522B47E6612&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcrypto-is-illegal-in-china-binance-does-90-billion-of-business-there-anyway-2a0af975&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国证券交易委员会正在分别起诉币安和 Coinbase 两大加密货币平台。 《华尔街日报》的凯特琳·奥斯特罗夫 (Caitlin Ostroff) 详细分析了这些诉讼及其对加密货币行业的潜在影响。图片插图：Adam Adada/沉星培<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>据《华尔街日报》此前报道，币安在中国保留了数十名员工。其美国分公司的高管担心这一安排的影响，包括中国开发商控制美国用户数据。</p><p>赵过去曾表示，他和其他员工的中国血统被用来描绘与国家的密切关系。</p><p> “币安今天面临的最大挑战是我们（以及所有其他离岸交易所）已被指定为中国的犯罪实体。与此同时，西方的反对派不遗余力地将我们描绘成一家‘中国公司’，”他去年<a href="https://www.binance.com/en/blog/from-cz/who-is-guangying-chen-and-is-binance-a-chinese-company-2386330931319516973" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在博客中写道</a>。</p><p>中国在 2021 年扩大了对该行业的打击力度，并宣布所有与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-declares-bitcoin-and-other-cryptocurrency-transactions-illegal-11632479288?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加密货币相关的交易都是非法的</a>。其动机是为了维护国家安全和社会稳定。</p><p>当时，币安表示将对平台用户进行清查，并将中国客户的账户切换为“仅限提款”模式，这意味着他们将被禁止进行交易。</p><p> “币安始终认真履行合规义务，始终严格遵守当地监管机构的相关要求，”币安在 2021 年 10 月的声明中表示。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827535?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国监管机构起诉币安创始人赵长鹏，指控其非法经营和滥用客户资金。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Anthony Kwan/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国官员似乎对这项全面禁令的实施采取了温和的态度。</p><p> “中国的加密货币市场依然强劲，中心化和（去中心化）服务的交易量都很健康，”加密货币研究公司 Chainaanalysis 的研究总监 Kim Grauer 表示。根据 Chainaanalysis 的数据，尽管 2021 年禁令颁布后最初有所下降，但该国仍是第四大加密货币交易市场。</p><p>币安的竞争对手火币交易所已促使中国用户<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/huobis-new-boss-shakes-up-crypto-firm-with-china-plan-94d65efb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">申请多米尼加数字公民身份</a>，以便他们能够在该平台上进行交易。</p><p>赵是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-crypto-side-door-buying-a-digital-residency-in-palau-for-248-1cd40643?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">帕劳向外国人出售居留卡项目</a>的最初发起人，不过币安表示最终放弃了与该项目的进一步联系。据一位知情人士透露，币安对帕劳计划感兴趣的部分原因是希望帮助中国用户。</p><p>中国和其他地方的加密货币交易者也使用VPN（一种掩盖其位置的应用程序）来注册在其国家/地区被禁止的交易所。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p><em>币安在中国的未来是什么？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p>一位查看数据的前员工表示，禁令生效后，币安的中国业务占其总交易量的比例从年中的 24% 降至 2021 年底的 17%。</p><p>但在2022年再次回升，并一直保持在高位。根据币安名为“Mission Control”的内部平台的数据，2023 年 5 月，中国客户的加密货币交易量超过 900 亿美元。大部分交易都是与加密货币相关的期货合约。美国禁止加密货币期货交易</p><p>据 Mission Control 称，该交易所有 560 万中国用户注册，其中 911,650 名活跃用户。</p><p>该交易所的第二大市场是韩国，占 13% 的份额， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turks-pile-into-bitcoin-and-tether-to-escape-plunging-lira-11641982077?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">其次是土耳其，</a>占近 10%。所有其他国家/地区的交易量不到币安交易量的 5%。</p><p>根据公司内部文件和一名前员工的说法，截至 1 月份，币安约有 10 万中国用户被归类为“政治人物”。银行和监管机构使用 PEP 称号来标记政府官员、其亲属或亲密伙伴，因为他们参与贿赂、腐败或洗钱的风险较大，因此需要接受更严格的审查。</p><p>根据内部文件和这位前员工的说法，币安过去对验证中国用户的身份采取了宽松的态度​​。在 2021 年底禁令生效后的几个月内，只有不到一半的中国注册用户接受了了解你的客户检查。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Vicky Ge Huang</em>对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Patricia Kowsmann <a href="mailto:patricia.kowsmann@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（patricia.kowsmann@wsj.com）</a>和 Caitlin Ostroff（ <a href="mailto:caitlin.ostroff@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">caitlin.ostroff@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-is-illegal-in-china-binance-does-90-billion-of-business-there-anyway-2a0af975</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-is-illegal-in-china-binance-does-90-billion-of-business-there-anyway-2a0af975<author><![CDATA[Patricia KowsmannCaitlin Ostroff]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>证券/商品交易活动</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>加密货币交易所</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币/加密货币</category><category>Corporate Crime/Legal Action</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉